snippet.textDisplay:
So Microsoft says they've designed this console to do 4k 60 fps. That's all fine but you can bet the devs are going to use this increase in graphical performace for higher graphics quality details and effects, such as ambient occlusion, shadows, textures, etc. instead of higher resolution and fps. Because otherwise what you get is a game that looks like what they make today except outputting at native 4k and 60 fps. Which most people would be happy with but to get more realistic and lifelike graphics you need to increase the graphics quality settings and also come up with additional effects, like ray tracing, that don't exist this generation. Which to be honest ray tracing is the only one they've come up with. The thing is the more you increase the graphics settings, the more you have to compromise on resolution and/or fps. You have this dilemma every time on pc. On console they have been giving people a taste of that dilemma by allowing players to choose between performance and resolution mode.



Another thing is that there are settings that depend on the cpu. Such as Level of Detail and enemy AI, etc. Look at Assassin's Creed Odyssey, for example, eventhough a high-end graphics card could have no problem holding up, the cpu may bottleneck and cause the game to run at a lower fps, because the game has so much calculations that it needs to do each frame in order to determine where each element (enemy, animal, boat, etc.) is in the game, what state it's in, etc.



So it's really up to the devs and the game they are making, what graphical detail level, resolution and fps they aim for. So having a console that can do 4k 60 fps is not a guarantee that's what it will do. Heck the xbox one could also do 4k 60 fps I bet if you run a 2d indie or SNES game on it.

snippet.textDisplay: The newly acquired MS studios are currently working on 40+ games, with another 20 or so unannounced, and this is around a year before the console is even available. Couple that with Game Pass and the fact that this console will support backwards compatibility for all  previously supported titles, and hopefully that will be enough to break the "xbox has no games" stigma. Probably not though... We know how the "console war" goes, as well as this apparent deep-seeded animosity towards MS among the community.

snippet.textDisplay: I don’t think PC will become non existent nor do I expect a see Console gaming going away.. I look to see them becoming less and less Diverged.. I think with X-cloud, if it goes like it has been, we will see more and more gaming through the internet.. So will we one day be able to play a game with the best possible graphics with the highest price video cards for everyone.. I can’t wait for that day.. the Xbox series X will be interesting, but if X-Cloud works well, I think in the future we will play that way more and more, but Xbox Series S only uses the cloud then do we wait a year to get it? Odd timing on the release..
